1381","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","1438":"1438","Hatherton, Cheshire, England":"Hatherton, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"en":{"1381–1438":"1381–1438","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","1407–1487":"1407–1487","about 1407":"about 1407","1487":"1487","1385":"1385","1381":"1381","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","1438":"1438","Hatherton, Cheshire, England":"Hatherton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  .","History: Walter Corbet, a royal knight in 12th-century Scotland, was the first of that name in that kingdom. His 13th-century descendants were major landholders in the Borders, and in the 14th century they acquired lands in the North of Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbett","meanings":["English (West Midlands, of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>corbet</i> ‘raven’, probably denoting someone with dark hair or a dark complexion.","History: This is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Corbet I was born in 1381, in Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales. He married Mary Corbet in 1406, in Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1438, in his hometown, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1381–1438":"1381–1438","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1407–1487":"1407–1487","about 1407":"umbes 1407","1487":"1487","1385":"1385","1381":"1381","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","1438":"1438","Hatherton, Cheshire, England":"Hatherton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1381–1438":"1381–1438","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1407–1487":"1407–1487","about 1407":"noin 1407","1487":"1487","1385":"1385","1381":"1381","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","1438":"1438","Hatherton, Cheshire, England":"Hatherton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1381–1438":"1381–1438","1385–Female":"1385–Décédée","1407–1487":"1407–1487","about 1407":"environ 1407","1487":"1487","1385":"1385","1381":"1381","1407":"1407","1406":"1406","1438":"1438","Hatherton, Cheshire, England":"Hatherton, Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Leighton, Montgomeryshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Robert Corbet I est né en 1381, 